    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-02-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="513"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d513">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/2–749</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Secretary of State of a Conversation With
                        President Truman</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-02-07">February 7,
                            1949</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President has given further thought to the recommendation of the National
                    Security Council on munitions to China in the light of the advice given him by
                    the Congressional leaders. He believes that it is wise for us to follow that
                    advice. Therefore, we will not suspend or embargo shipments to China. However,
                    wherever possible, it is desirable that shipments be delayed where this can be
                    done without formal action. I suspect that this means that the ships now loading
                    should be permitted to sail.</p>
                <p>I should like a report on how other shipments from the United States and surplus
                    property shipments from the Far East can be slowed down.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>D[<hi rend="smallcaps">ean</hi>] A[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >cheson</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
